      "description": "The drum kit on God Hates Us All centered on a Tama Starclassic Maple — Tama's flagship all-maple shell series in the early 2000s. The choice reflected both the band's long-standing Tama endorsement (going back to Lombardo's Artstar II era) and Matt Hyde's preference for a warmer, more resonant low-end on the drums than Slayer's classic dry sound.\n\nThe double bass configuration of two 22x18 kicks gave the album the deep, sustained low-end that suited Hyde's modern production approach. The shells' 18-inch depth — deeper than the 16-inch kicks of the Reign in Blood era — added body and resonance that Hyde captured with port-mic plus inside-mic technique. The low-end on God Hates Us All sits noticeably heavier in the mix than on earlier Slayer records, and the kit specification is one of the reasons.\n\nThe tom configuration kept Slayer's classic 4-piece approach: two rack toms (10 and 12) and two floor toms (16 and 18). The slightly larger 18-inch floor tom — instead of the more common 16 — gave the lower fills additional weight, audible on tracks like \"Bloodline\" and \"Disciple\" where the tom work punctuates the riff structure.\n\nThe Piano Black finish maintained the dark visual aesthetic of Slayer's gear catalog — a constant from Show No Mercy through the band's entire career.",
