      "description": "The snare drum on God Hates Us All was a 14x6.5 steel-shell — the standard size and material for thrash metal records of the era. Steel gave the snare the cutting, metallic crack that Slayer's music demands, with the 6.5-inch depth providing the body needed to translate through Matt Hyde's modern, layered production.\n\nThe snare sound on God Hates Us All is one of the most aggressive of the entire Slayer catalog. Hyde compressed it heavily — a deliberate departure from the more transparent Rick Rubin approach of the 1980s — and placed it forward in the mix. The result is the snare crack on \"Bloodline\" and \"Disciple\" hits with a brutality that defined the album's overall sonic character.\n\nThe 6.5-inch depth was a slight increase over the 6-inch and 5.5-inch snares more common on the classic Slayer records, contributing to the lower midrange weight that distinguishes the God Hates Us All sound. The combination of steel shell and deeper depth gave the snare both cut at the top and body underneath — necessary attributes for the album's down-tuned guitar context.",
